\begin_layout Subsubsection
Riemannian manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 be a Riemannian manifold (it will be the fiber) and let 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}\Phi$
\end_inset

 be the cotangent manifold.
 When supplied with coordinate charts, it can be locally trivialized as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left.T^{*}\Phi\right|_{U}\cong U\times\mathbb{R}^{n}
\]

\end_inset

and given canonical coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q^{1},\cdots,q^{n},p_{1},\cdots p_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 Then given a metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

, the Hamiltonian function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H\left(q,p\right)=\frac{1}{2}g^{ij}\left(q\right)p_{i}p_{j}
\]

\end_inset

provides the geodesic flow via the Hamilton-Jacobi equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{q}^{i}=\frac{\partial H}{\partial p_{i}}\quad\mbox{ and }\quad\dot{p}_{i}=-\frac{\partial H}{\partial q^{i}}
\]

\end_inset

Its a Hamiltonian flow, and 
\begin_inset Formula $dH/dt=0$
\end_inset

 on integral curves (geodesics).
 Symmetric spaces are always geodesically complete (Reimannian manifolds
 are not; see [[geodesic manifold]] wikipedia, but also Jost).
 Also, cotangent bundles are always symplectic manifolds, so come a tautological
 one-form and a symplectic form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Pushforwards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:M\to\Phi$
\end_inset

 be a section.
 Fixing 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in M$
\end_inset

 the pushforward 
\begin_inset Formula $d\phi_{x}:T_{x}M\to T_{\phi\left(x\right)}\Phi$
\end_inset

 is a map of tangent spaces, taking 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{\mu}\mapsto\frac{\partial\phi^{i}}{\partial x^{\mu}}\partial_{i}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mu}=\partial/\partial x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is a vector field in 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{i}=\partial/\partial q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is vector field in 
\begin_inset Formula $T\Phi$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix components are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(d\phi\right)_{\mu}^{i}=\frac{\partial\phi^{i}}{\partial x^{\mu}}=\partial_{\mu}\phi^{i}
\]

\end_inset

Its a diferential form, in that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\phi\left(\partial_{\mu}\right)=\left(\partial_{\mu}\phi^{i}\right)\partial_{i}
\]

\end_inset

and so that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\phi_{x}\in T_{x}^{*}M\times T_{\phi\left(x\right)}\Phi$
\end_inset

.
 We can explicitly write 
\begin_inset Formula $d\phi=\left(\partial_{\mu}\phi^{i}\right)dx^{\mu}\partial_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $dx^{\mu}\left(\partial_{\nu}\right)=\delta_{\nu}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 as always.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Metrics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each distinct section 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:M\to\Phi$
\end_inset

 induces a bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 via it's pushforward.
 (huh, the vielbeins are pushforwards, but the metric itself is a pullback,
 in that we pulled 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 back to 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{\mu\nu}\left(\phi\right)=g_{ij}\partial_{\mu}\phi^{i}\partial_{\nu}\phi^{j}
\]

\end_inset

Each factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mu}\phi^{i}$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as a vielbein.
 This is a symmetric bilenear form, it would be a metric if and only if
 it was invertible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since both 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 are Riemannian manifolds, both have the momenta on the cotangent-thing
 going, and we are gluing the momenta together, which means that the 
\begin_inset Formula $d\phi$
\end_inset

 is a solder form.
 (Technically, a solder form has to be an isomorphism; this requires the
 real dimensions of the base and target space to be equal.
 Also, by convention the target of a solder form is a Lie group.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Harmonic forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\in\Omega^{p}\left(M\right)$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-forms with compact support.
 Define the point-wise inner product as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \alpha,\beta\right\rangle =*\left(\alpha\wedge*\beta\right)
\]

\end_inset

and the manifold-wise product 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\alpha,\beta\right)=\int_{M}\left\langle \alpha,\beta\right\rangle *\left(1\right)=\int_{M}\alpha\wedge*\beta
\]

\end_inset

be thier 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset

 product on Sobolev space.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(d\alpha,\beta\right)=\left(\alpha,\delta\beta\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\left(-1\right)^{n\left(p+1\right)+1}*d*$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\delta d+d\delta$
\end_inset

 is the Laplace-deRham operator.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\Delta\alpha,\beta\right)=\left(\alpha,\Delta\beta\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g$
\end_inset

 are functions, not forms, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta f=\delta g=0$
\end_inset

 and one has
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(df,dg\right)=\left(f,\Delta g\right)
\]

\end_inset

The sigma model is of course
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{S}\left(\phi\right)=\frac{1}{2}\int_{M}d\phi\wedge*d\phi=\left(d\phi,d\phi\right)
\]

\end_inset

where from the point of view of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a scalar function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sigma model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sigma model Lagrangain can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}\left(\phi\right)=\frac{1}{2}d\phi\wedge*d\phi
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:M\to\Phi$
\end_inset

 a section.
 Equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}=\frac{1}{2}g_{ij}\left(\phi\right)\left(\partial^{\mu}\phi^{i}\right)\left(\partial_{\mu}\phi^{j}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is a Riemannian metric on the field space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mu}\phi$
\end_inset

 is a section of the jet bundle of 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times\Phi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-dimensional, 
\begin_inset Formula $*d\phi=\wedge^{m-1}T^{*}M$
\end_inset

 and its silly to try to write it explicitly, because
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta\wedge*\zeta=\left\langle \eta,\zeta\right\rangle \omega
\]

\end_inset

by defintion, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 the volume form on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 the metric on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\phi\wedge*d\phi=\omega\partial_{\mu}\phi\partial^{\mu}\phi
\]

\end_inset

so we really do need to track the metric on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 distinctly.
 It's not implicitly handled.
 And the volume form is getting ditched on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 so that's ugly/confusing.
 Bleh.
 There must be a prettier way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Matrix identities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following matrix identity is very useful: given a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{-X}de^{X}=dX-\frac{1}{2!}\left[X,dX\right]+\frac{1}{3!}\left[X,\left[X,dX\right]\right]-\cdots
\]

\end_inset

which is easy to verify by direct computation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $X=X^{i}e_{i}$
\end_inset

 for Lie-algebra-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 obeying 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[e_{i},e_{j}\right]=f_{ij}^{\;\,k}e_{k}$
\end_inset

 one then obtains 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
e^{-X}de^{X} & =dX^{i}e_{i}-\frac{1}{2!}X^{i}dX^{j}f_{ij}^{\;\,k}e_{k}+\frac{1}{3!}X^{i}X^{j}dX^{k}f_{jk}^{\;\,l}f_{il}^{\;m}e_{m}-\cdots\\
 & =e_{i}W_{ij}dX^{j}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\left(-1\right)^{n}M^{n}}{\left(n+1\right)!}=\left(I-e^{-M}\right)M^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

where the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has matrix elements
\begin_inset Formula $M_{j}^{\,k}=X^{i}f_{ij}^{\;\,k}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is a vielbein, in that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{ij}=W_{i}^{\,m}W_{\;j}^{n}\kappa_{mn}
\]

\end_inset

is a Riemannian metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}$
\end_inset

 that is a pullback of the Killing form 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{mn}=f_{im}^{\;\,j}f_{jn}^{\;\,i}$
\end_inset

.
 The Killing form can be taken as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 metric on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

.
 Whenever a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

curved
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 matric can be written in terms of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 metric in this way, the factors 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{i}^{\,m}$
\end_inset

 are called the vielbeins.
 Cool! Note the second vielbein is a transpose!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be plugged directly into the sigma model Lagrangian.
 That is, let 
\begin_inset Formula $L=U^{\dagger}dU$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\exp\vec{T}\cdot\vec{\theta}$
\end_inset

 and write the Killing form as 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{mn}=c\,\mbox{tr}T_{m}T_{n}$
\end_inset

 for appropriate constant 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 which depends on the algebra.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\,\mbox{tr}L\wedge*L=g_{ij}d\theta^{i}\wedge*d\theta^{j}=W_{i}^{\,m}W_{\;j}^{n}\;d\theta^{i}\wedge*d\theta^{j}\;c\,\mbox{tr}T_{m}T_{n}
\]

\end_inset

which is a fairly slick trick.
 Note the second 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is a transpose of the first.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sigma model redux
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From what I can tell, Yilmaz is saying that the above can even work for
 the symmetric space, in that one can split, with some care, the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 into those that are in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{h}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}=\mathfrak{m\oplus\mathfrak{h}}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, one can write a parameterization for 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi=e^{\theta^{i}m_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}$
\end_inset

 the basis vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\#$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generalized transpose
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 , induced by the Cartan involution 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\#}=-\alpha\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\mathfrak{g}$
