\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a compact connected Lie group.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:G\to G$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(gg^{\prime}\right)=\alpha\left(g\right)\alpha\left(g^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 and also 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{2}\left(g\right)=\alpha\left(\alpha\left(g\right)\right)=g$
\end_inset

.
 This is the definition of an involution; it is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the Cartan involution
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The fixed points 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in G$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 are by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(h\right)=h$
\end_inset

.
 These form a subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H\subset G$
\end_inset

 and the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 is a symmetric space – by defintion, symmetric spaces are quotients of
 a group by it's involution-invariant subgroup.
 It's assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is non-trivial, 
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a proper subgroup that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is not the trivial subgroup.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This function 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as a permutation of two 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

parts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

; the subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is then the diagonal of a product of these two parts.
 Later on, these will be identified as the left and right chiral pieces
 of the sigma model; there is no need to do this, yet, and so the following
 proceeds in a generic fashion.
 (There are actually three possibilities: 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a real simple Lie group, or 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the product of two compact simple Lie groups (this is the conventional
 sigma model) or 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the complexification of a compact simple Lie group, in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 is non-compact, and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the maximal compact subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding Lie algbera of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 descends to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 the identity, it's eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 It splits 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 into odd and even subspaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}=\mathfrak{m}\oplus\mathfrak{h}$
\end_inset

.
 The odd-parity subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 can be identified as the tangent space of 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 at the identity and the even-parity subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{h}$
\end_inset

 is the Lie algebra of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 Note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathfrak{h},\mathfrak{h}\right]\subseteq\mathfrak{h}\quad\mbox{ and }\quad\left[\mathfrak{m},\mathfrak{h}\right]\subseteq\mathfrak{m}\quad\mbox{ and }\quad\left[\mathfrak{m},\mathfrak{m}\right]\mathfrak{\subseteq h}
\]

\end_inset

The easiest way to see this is to note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left[X,Y\right]=\left[\alpha\left(X\right),\alpha\left(Y\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y\in\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $X=X_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus X_{\mathfrak{h}}$
\end_inset

 and note the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(X_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus X_{\mathfrak{h}}\right)=\left(-X_{\mathfrak{m}}\right)\oplus X_{\mathfrak{h}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then clearly the parity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[X_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus0,0\oplus Y_{\mathfrak{h}}\right]$
\end_inset

 is negative, while the parity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0\oplus X_{\mathfrak{h}},0\oplus Y_{\mathfrak{h}}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[X_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus0,Y_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus0\right]$
\end_inset

 is positive.
\end_layout

